{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6ed38c47-c165-4a4b-800b-4086b94713bb","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. In MAUI, there are no HTTP requests — so a \"scope\" is effectively the **entire app lifetime**. This means `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`, and your `DbContext` (and its change tracker) lives forever, leaking stale data across navigations.\n\n**Fix:** Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()` so each injection gets a fresh instance, or create scopes manually with `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n\n```csharp\nusing var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\nvar db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n```\n\nThis is one of the most common DI pitfalls when moving from ASP.NET Core to MAUI.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e0def43e-9f84-40cd-b0e3-b15c86dbdf8c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common gotcha when transitioning from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and `DbContext`. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly — no tools needed.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request, so `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton` — the same instance lives for the entire app lifetime. That's why the DbContext's change tracker retains stale data across navigations.","outputTokens":348,"requestId":"1112:2D596F:C790E8:E944D7:69FE8807"},"id":"bc8a566e-0a89-4e49-876b-70f5e03ed2ae","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:04:15.681Z","parentId":"5f644e43-bda6-4480-ac9f-dd05b5778ce6"}
